                        <h1>HOT NEWS</h1>
                        <h2><a href="news/06-07-18_500_million_contrac.html">Largest
                            state employees union ratifies new $500 million contract </a></h2>
                        <p align="center"><img src="news/images/videojuly15.jpg" alt="Largest state employees union ratifies new $500 million contract " width="261" height="175" border="1"></p>
                        <p><em>July 15, 2006 - Associated Press</em></p>
                        <p>The largest state employees union has ratified what
                          union officials called their biggest contract ever,
                          a package that could be worth $500 million over three
                          years. The contract was approved by 94 percent of Service
                          Employees International Union Local 1000's 85,000 members
                          after a monthlong vote, the union said Saturday. </p>
                      </div>
                      <h2><a href="news/06-07-24_security_guard_unionization.html">Security
                      Guard Unionization Heats Up </a></h2>
                      <p>Campaigners for security officers across Los Angeles
                        County, the majority of whom are African-American, have
                        expressed cautious optimism in their battle to unionize
                        the industry and secure better pay and improved working
                        conditions. Nearly 70 percent of security officers are
                        black and live well below the poverty line, according
                        to the Stand for Security Coalition, an advocacy group
                        comprised of security officers, union activists and church
                        and community leaders.                      </p>
                      <h1 align="center">Longtime Labor Leader <br>
                        Armando Vergara Passes </h1>
                      <p><img src="news/images/armando.jpg" alt="Aramando Vergara" width="123" height="175" hspace="10" border="1" align="right">Aramando
                        Vergara, long time labor leader who spent most of his
                        career with the United Brotherhood of Carpenters and
                        Joiners of America, lost his life on July 14th to Cancer.
                        Armando first joined the Carpenters Union in 1950 and
                        advanced steadily through leadership ranks to be elected
                        to the General Executive Board&rsquo;s 8th District.
                        He was also a National Founding Member of the Labor Council
                        for Latin American Advancement (LCLAA).                      </p>
                      <blockquote>
                        <p><em><strong>In lieu of flowers the Vergara familyrequests
                        that donations be made to:</strong></em></p>
                        <p>California Golden Gloves<br>
                          1838 Peterson Avenue<br>
                          South Pasadena, CA 91030</p>
                      </blockquote>
                      <h2><a href="news/06-07-24_critical_condition.html">Critical
                          Condition </a></h2>
                      <p>Will the NLRB deny nurses union cards? The nurses wore
                        red t-shirts depicting three 1950s-era RNs flexing their
                        muscles. &ldquo;The estrogen is high today!&rdquo; said
                        one, marching down Wilshire Boulevard in the glare of
                        L.A.&rsquo;s noonday sun. Indeed, it was on July 11 when
                        she and 300 of her fellow members of the mostly female
                        California Nurses Association and their supporters rallied
                        at the National Labor Relations Board&rsquo;s offices
                        on Figueroa Street. </p>
                      <h2><a href="news/06-07-24_apala.html">APALA to Hold Annual
                        Organizer Training in Los Angeles, Sept. 22-24 </a></h2>
                      <p><img src="news/images/apala.jpg" alt="APALA" width="73" height="77" hspace="10" border="1" align="left">The Asian Pacific American Labor Alliance (APALA) will
                        be holding its annual Organizer Training on September
                        22-24, 2006 in Los Angeles. This training is a unique
                        opportunity to learn from the best Asian and Pacific
                        Islander American union organizers in the country and
                        be placed in entry-level organizing positions or gain
                        the skills needed to participate in your union&rsquo;s
                        organizing programs.</p>
                      <h2><a href="news/06-07-18_shakeel_syed.html">Shakeel
                        Syed on his arrest on July 29 in support of Hilton
                        workers </a></h2>
                      <p><img src="news/images/HiltonCivilDisobedience pic.jpg" alt="Shakeel Syed on his arrest on July 29 in support of Hilton workers" width="205" height="135" hspace="10" border="1" align="right">Gray
                        haired Father Estrada was first to be arrested. He looked
                        just as peaceful as an infant enjoying his slumber. Sean's
                        youthful energy was infectious. Jason was chanting silently
                        basking in setting sun. Amanda just couldn't stop smiling.
                        I was next. For the first time in my two decade life
                        in United States, in a public square, proudly ready for
                        my arrest. Facing me was the towering Hilton and sitting
                        on the Century Blvd. </p>
                      <h2><a href="news/06-07-14_un-faithful.html">Pastor is
                          un-Faithful on promises to union </a></h2>
                      <p><img src="news/images/060720_forum_s.jpg" alt="Pastor is un-Faithful on promises to union" width="250" height="152" hspace="10" border="1" align="left">The dispute between the Faithful Central Bible Church-owned
                        Forum and a slew of workers who keep the massive facility
                        functioning, was ratcheted up a few knots Sunday and
                        Monday when more than 300 assorted union members from
                        around Los Angeles descended upon the arena to demonstrate
                        at the long-awaited Pearl Jam concert. The Forum&rsquo;s
                        stagehands, janitors, operating and building engineers
                        and their supporters picketed Pearl Jam to protest the
                        workers&rsquo; claims that some have been forced-out
                        of their Forum jobs during the past three years and others
                        have been locked-out of them since April 10. </p>
                      <h2><a href="news/06-07-11_immigration_reform.html">Unions
                          Discuss Immigration Reform at NCLR Town Hall </a></h2>
                      <p><img src="news/images/NCLR-Con.jpg" alt="Unions Discuss Immigration Reform at NCLR Town Hall " width="231" height="154" hspace="10" border="1" align="right">In
                        keeping with the labor movement&rsquo;s commitment to
                        immigrant workers AFSCME, the Los Angeles County Federation
                        of Labor, AFL-CIO, SEIU International, UFW and UNITE
                        HERE! took part in an immigration town hall hosted by
                        the National Council of La Raza (NCLR) at their annual
                        convention in Los Angeles this past weekend.</p>
                      <h2><a href="news/06-07-11_garment_industry.html">New Book
                          Highlights Struggles of Asian Americans in the Garment
                          Industry</a></h2>
                      <p><img src="news/images/sweatshopslaves.gif" width="98" height="106" hspace="10" border="1" align="left">UCLA
                        students along with the UCLA Center for Labor Research
                        and Education have released a new book titled <em>Sweatshop
                        Slaves: Asian Americans in the Garment Industry. </em>To
                        purchase a copy of the book please call (310) 206-0812
                        or e-mail <a href="mailto:egrove@iir.ucla.edu">egrove@iir.ucla.edu</a>.
                        You may also visit <a href="http://www.labor.ucla.edu/publications/index.html" target="_blank">www.labor.ucla.edu/publications/index.html</a>.</p>
                      <h2><a href="news/06-07-11_anti-corporate_pearl_jam.html">Anti-Corporate
                          Pearl Jam Crosses Picket Line </a></h2>
                      <p><img src="news/images/060712_2s.jpg" alt="Anti-Corporate Pearl Jam Crosses Picket Line " width="150" height="121" hspace="10" border="1" align="right">Pearl
                        Jam, known for its outspoken anti-corporate position,
                        crossed the picket line at the LA Forum on July 9 as
                        more than 200 IATSE 33 members and Los Angles union members
                        protested wage cuts of up to 35 percent. <br>
                        Visit: <a href="http://www.JusticeAtTheForum.com/" target="_blank">www.JusticeAtTheForum.com</a> </p>
                      <h2>L.A. janitors get boost from City Council </h2>
                      <p><em>The Hollywood Reporter</em></p>
                      <p>The Los Angeles City Council unanimously passed a resolution
                        Wednesday calling on certain Southern California entertainment
                        companies to improve wages and conditions for the janitors
                        that work at their facilities. The resolution names several
                        studios and companies &mdash; including ABC, CBS, NBC
                        Universal, Hollywood Center Studios, Raleigh Studios
                        and Warner Music Group &mdash; that allegedly employ
                        nonunion janitors and do not offer affordable medical
                        benefits.</p>
                      <h2><a href="pdf/press/06_07_05_dolores.pdf" target="_blank">LA
                          Labor and the Los Angeles Community College District
                          Launch the Dolores Huerta Labor Institute </a></h2>
                      <p align="center"><em><strong><img src="news/images/060707_1.jpg" alt="LA Labor and the Los Angeles Community College District Launch the Dolores Huerta Labor Institute" width="250" height="167" border="1"><br>
                        10 local unions to fund the <br>
                        institute in it&rsquo;s first three years</strong></em></p>
                      <p>Educators, labor and community leaders gathered last
                        week for the unveiling of the Dolores Huerta Labor Institute
                        at the Los Angeles Community College District Offices.
                        Several Los Angeles local unions including AFT Local
                        1521, IBEW Locals 11 and 18, Longshoremen Local 63, Plumbers
                        and Pipefitters District Council 16 and Local 250, SEIU
                        Locals 347, 660, UHW and UFCW Locals 770 and 1442, have
                        all agreed to contribute $10,000 a year for the next
                        three years which will help the institute in it&rsquo;s
                        start-up phase.</p>
                      <h2><a href="news/06-07-05_hilton_hotel_workers.html">Immigrant
                          Rights Leaders Participate in Civil Disobedience Action
                          in Show of Support for Hilton Hotel Workers </a></h2>
                      <p>Immigrant rights activists, community members, clergy,
                        and hotel workers marched on Century Blvd. last week
                        in support of Glendale and LAX Hilton hotel workers who
                        are fighting for living wages and health care by organizing
                        to form a union (UNITE HERE Local 11). The action lead
                        to several arrests for civil disobedience.</p>
                      <h2><a href="news/06-06-21_summer_programming.html">Labor&rsquo;s
                          Hollywood Summer Programming</a></h2>
                      <p>On a broiling afternoon last Thursday, International
                        Justice for Janitors Day, 200 purple-shirted members
                        of the Service Employees International Union (SEIU) rallied
                        for contracts at companies where they now hold none.
                        They did not march past the usual downtown high-rises
                        or aerospace-industry bunkers, but at CityWalk, the Universal
                        Studios tourist attraction that presents visitors with
                        an airbrushed simulacrum of the Los Angeles they sweep,
                        mop and vacuum every day. Chanting in Spanish before
                        signs for Abercrombie and Fitch, Zen Zone oxygen bar
                        and a giant cutout of King Kong, the janitors from Local
                        1877 bewildered tourists seeking shade and a place to
                        spend money.</p>
                      <h2>Senate Investigates Allegations that Hilton Abuses
                        Immigrant Workers</h2>
                      <p><img src="images/UNITE%20HERE%20Hearing_m.jpg" width="120" height="180" hspace="10" border="1" align="left">Earlier
                        this month, the California State Senate Committee on
                        Labor and Industrial Relations held an informational
                        hearing on allegations that the Hilton Hotel Corporation
                        has been mistreating its immigrant workforce. Several
                        Hilton workers testified alleging that working conditions
                        at the hotel have contributed to an increase in injuries
                        and violations of state meal and break period laws. The
                        management of the LAX Hilton was asked to testify, but
                        declined.</p>
                      <p align="left">A recent report claims that just in the
                        last year, there were almost 1,000 (931) injuries to
                        workers in just 27 Hilton properties. At the LAX Hilton,
                        20% of the housekeepers were injured on the job in 2005.
                        Most of these workers are immigrant women.</p>
                      <h2 align="left"><a href="news/06-06-20_krug_mondavi.html">Join
                          the Krug-Mondavi Wine Boycott &amp; Help Save Jobs</a></h2>
                      <p>Charles Krug-Mondavi workers are calling for a nationwide
                        boycott of their company's products&#8212;Charles Krug
                        and C.K. Mondavi wine labels&#8212;in an effort to save
                        their jobs. They ask you to send an immediate e-mail
                        to the company supporting their boycott.</p>
                      <p>Send your message today. Go to: <a href="http://www.ufwaction.org/campaign/krugboycott" target="_blank">http://www.ufwaction.org/campaign/krugboycott</a>.<br>
                        &nbsp;</p>
