                        <td width="240"><h2><a href="news/06-07-24_los_robles _medical_center.html">1000
                              Caregivers Authorize Strike at HCA/Los Robles Medical
                              Center
                        </a></h2>
                          <p>On July 19, 90% of voting caregivers at HCA/Los
                            Robles Medical Center authorized their elected Bargaining
                            Committee to schedule a one-day strike if good faith
                            contract talks with hospital management do not progress.
                            Approximately 1000 Registered Nurses, Licensed Vocational
                            Nurses, Certified Nursing Assistants, Technicians,
                            Respiratory Therapists, Dietary Aides, and Environmental
                            Service Workers and other healthcare workers are
                            represented by SEIU United Healthcare Workers-West
                            and SEIU 121 RN at the HCA/Los Robles. No strike
                          date has been set.</p>
                          <h2><a href="news/06-07-19_maria_elena _durazo.html">Los
                            Angeles County Federation of Labor Unanimously
                            Endorses of Education Reform Legislation AB 1381 </a></h2>
                          <p>&ldquo;Working families spoke loud and clear last
                            night when they unanimously endorsed AB 1381.,&rdquo; said
                            Durazo. &ldquo;There is no doubt that our educational
                            system is in crisis when 50% of our African American
                            and Latino students do not graduate in four years.
                            Only 22% of 9th graders are ready for college. </p>
                          <h2><a href="news/06-07-12_nurses_hold_action.html">Nurses
                          Hold Action Against Attacks on Workers Rights</a></h2>
                          <p><img src="news/images/060712_1s.jpg" alt="Nurses Hold Action Against Attacks on Workers Rights" width="200" height="150" hspace="10" border="1"><br>
                            In an effort to fight back the latest attempt by
                              the Bush appointed National Labor Relations Board
                              (NLRB) against our workers, CNA, AFSCME-UNAC, AFTRA,
                              Building Trades, IATSE Western Region and Locals
                              44, 80 and 705, IBEW, Local 11, NABET CWA, SEIU-UHW
                              and 121 RN, Steel Workers and United Firefighters
                              of Los Angeles City, Local 112 attended an action
                              on July 11th in support of our nurses.</p>
                          <h2><a href="news/06-07-05_record-breaking_settlement.html">Supermarket
                            Workers Locked Out by Ralphs in 2003 to Receive
                            Record-Breaking Settlement From Grocer </a></h2>
                          <p> Last week Ralphs Grocery Company admitted to their
                            employees that they had violated the law during the
                            2003-04 lockout and had reached a settlement with
                            the U.S. Attorney. This record-shattering settlement,
                            which will be contingent on court approval as well
                            as the withdrawal of the union&rsquo;s case pending
                            before the National Labor Relations Board, will end
                            the federal government&rsquo;s case against the company
                            for conspiracy, identity fraud, money laundering,
                            and obstruction of justice.</p>
                          <h2>Ralphs to Pay $70 Million for Illegal Hiring Scheme </h2>
                          <p>The Ralphs grocery chain said Friday that it had
                            agreed to pay $70 million in fines and restitution
                            to settle criminal charges that it illegally rehired
                            locked-out workers during the supermarket labor dispute
                            in Southern California more than two years ago<br>
                            <a href="news/06-07-05_illegal_hiring_scheme.html">Click
                            here </a>for the <em>LA Times</em> story</p>
                          <h2><a href="news/06-06-16_solidarity.html">The New
                              Face of Solidarity</a></h2>
                          <p> Manuel Alvarez is the type of worker that service-sector
                            unions are eager to attract. After 11 years as a
                            houseman at the Hilton Hotel at Los Angeles International
                            Airport, he earns $9.95 an hour, about $20,000 a
                            year.</p>
                          <h2 align="left"><a href="news/06-06-23_supreme_court.html">Justices
                              Define Employer Reprisal Liberally</a></h2>
                          <p><em>David G. Savage, LATimes</em></p>
                          <p>The Supreme Court on Thursday strengthened the enforcement
                            of civil rights laws in the workplace, ruling that
                            it is illegal for employers to punish workers who
                            file discrimination complaints by shifting them to
                            a less appealing job or changing their work hours.</p>
